An Experiment of Adaptive Metropolis

Ye (Eric) Wang

2/21/2017

This is an experiment on the performance of the adaptive Metropolis algorithm (Haario et al., 2001). For more details, see the original paper https://projecteuclid.org/euclid.bj/1080222083. Roughly speaking, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm (AM) adapts the covariance matrix of the proposal distribution using all the past samples.

To be more specific, let x1,x2,,xt be the t previous samples at time t+1, Haario et al. (2001) proposed to use a Gaussian distribution centered at xt as the proposal distribution. The covariance matrix of this proposal distribution, which is very important to the mixing of MCMC, is calculated as

sd cov(x1,,xt)+ sd eps diag(1,,1).

Create a Target Distribution

I used the AM algorithm to sample from a 10-dimensional centered Gaussian distribution and I used the following code to create a covariance matrix for this distribution. As can be seen, the covariance matrix is created in a way such that there tends to be a complicated correlation structure hence the standanrd metropolis (hastings) algorithm might suffer. The R code and demo can be found in https://github.com/ericyewang/adaptive_metropolis.

suppressMessages(require(mvtnorm))
p = 10 # dimension
Fc = matrix(rnorm(p*p),p,p) # loadings for the covariance matrix
C = Fc%*%t(Fc)+diag(0.1,p) # create a covariance matrix
ldens <- function(x,C){
  # log density function of the target distribution
  # up to a normalizing constant
  return(-t(x)%*%solve(C)%*%x)
}

AM Sampling

I used the following code to do AM sampling. Note that sd and eps are the tuning parameters and I fixed them at values recommended by Haario et al., 2001.

adaptiveMetropolis <- function(p,t0,t1,nm,sd_mh,ldens,...){
  # Adaptive Metropolis algorithm (am; Haario et al. 2001)
  # Args:
  #   p: dimension of the target distribution.
  #   t0: let the sampler run for t0 steps first under naive Metropolis algorithm,
  #       the samples before step t0 will not be used in the adaptation.
  #   t1: time when all samples afterwards will be used in the adaptation.
  #   nm: number of Metropolis samples.
  #   sd_mh: standard deviation for the proposal distribution of the naive Metropolis,
  #           note that the proposal is a homogeneous Gaussian.
  #   ldens: log density function of the target distribution.
  #   ...: optional arguments to ldens.
  
  # preparation
  sd = 2.4^2/p
  eps = 0.1
  sps = NULL
  sp = rep(0,p)
  C0 = diag(0.1,p)
  for (iter in 1:nm){
    # propose new sample
    if (iter <= t1){
      nsp = c(rmvnorm(1,sp,C0))
    }else {
      nsp = c(rmvnorm(1,sp,Ct))
    }
    lalpha = ldens(nsp,...)-ldens(sp,...)
    if (log(runif(1))<lalpha){
      sp = nsp
    }
    # store the samples
    sps = cbind(sps,sp)
    # update covariance estimate
    if (iter == t0+1){
      mut = sp
      Ct = sd*eps*diag(1,p)
    }
    if (iter > t0+1){
      citer = iter-t0-1
      tmpmu = (mut*(citer-1)+sp)/citer
      Ct = (citer-1)*Ct/citer+sd/citer*(citer*mut%*%t(mut)-(citer+1)*tmpmu%*%t(tmpmu)+
                                          sp%*%t(sp)+eps*diag(1,p))
      mut = tmpmu
    }
  }
  return(sps)
}


t0 = 200
t1 = t0+200
nm = 5000
sBeta = adaptiveMetropolis(p=p,t0=t0,t1=t1,nm=nm,sd_mh=0.1,ldens=ldens,C=C)

Standard Metropolis Algorithm

In order to demonstrate the performance of AM, I also did the following standard Metropolis algorithm.

nm = 5000
sBeta0 = NULL
beta = rep(0,p)
for (iter in 1:nm){
  # propose new beta
  nbeta = beta + 0.5*rnorm(10)
  lalpha = dmvnorm(nbeta,rep(0,p),C,log=TRUE)-dmvnorm(beta,rep(0,p),C,log=TRUE)
  if (log(runif(1))<lalpha){
    beta = nbeta
  }
  # store the samples
  sBeta0 = cbind(sBeta0,beta)
}
